<section id="findingsSection6a" class="ExecutiveFindings_general">
  <div class="container pt-5">
    <div class="row justify-content-center">
      <div class="col-md-11 mt-4">
        <h2 id="findingsS6" class="font-medium text-[#575796]">
          6. Project Design
        </h2>
        <p>
          To present an image that accurately reflects how justice is experienced by ordinary people, this report draws on data from the World Justice Project Global Legal Needs Survey (WJP GLNS), embedded in the 2024 <i>WJP EUROVOICES</i> General Population Poll (GPP). The WJP GLNS captures people’s experiences with justiciable problems and their pathways to resolution, thereby offering a people-centered view of justice.<sup>54</sup> At the same time, its integration into the GPP allows for the combination of this experiential evidence with broader perceptions of the justice system and its actors. 
        </p>
        <p>
          The concepts and measures employed in this report build upon a solid foundation of previous research conducted by the World Justice Project (WJP).<sup>55</sup> These publications advanced the measurement of justice by developing and analyzing outcome indicators around the pathways to justice, the prevalence and co-occurrence of justiciable problems, the extent of unmet justice needs in each country, and the sociodemographic disparities in accessing formal and informal justice systems. Building on this tradition, the present report provides not only insights into the justice system in Italy but also a broader analytical framework grounded in a people-centered justice perspective.
        </p>
        <h6 class="font-medium text-[#575796]">
          Data Collection
        </h6>
        <p>
          The survey sampling, fieldwork, and data processing in Italy were carried out by Bilendi & Respondi using an online survey, which allowed for a wide geographic reach while maintaining consistency in administration.
        </p>
        <p>
          Prior to fieldwork, significant efforts were made to ensure the accuracy, cultural appropriateness, and reliability of the instrument. The questionnaire was translated into Italian and carefully adapted to reflect local expressions and linguistic nuances. To further refine the instrument, a pilot survey was conducted. The pilot results were rigorously reviewed and validated, and adjustments were incorporated before the questionnaire was rolled out to the full sample.
        </p>
        <p>
          The survey was administered online between March 1 and April 1, 2024. A probability-based sampling strategy was employed to ensure that the sample reflected the demographic composition of the population. Specifically, respondents were selected to be representative across four key sociodemographic criteria: age, gender, income level, and degree of urbanization, the latter categorized into urban and rural areas. In addition, the sampling framework was designed to achieve representativeness at the NUTS-1 level for Italy, ensuring that results are valid not only at the national level but also across the five major regions: North-West (ITC), North-East (ITH), Centre (ITI), South (ITF), and Islands (ITG).
        </p>
        <p>
          To guarantee the reliability of responses, the survey incorporated several quality assurance measures. These included monitoring the minimum length of interviews and setting a threshold for the maximum number of “do not know” responses allowed per questionnaire. These checks helped filter out inattentive or low-quality responses, ensuring that the resulting dataset accurately reflected the perspectives of the general population.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="row justify-content-center mt-5 foot-note">
      <div class="col-md-11 mb-1">
        <p class="reference">
          <small>
            <sup>54</sup> While the WJP Global Legal Needs Survey captures the number and type of problems each individual has faced in the past two years, detailed information on their justice journey, hardships, legal capabilities, and outcomes is collected for only one issue. This focal problem is randomly selected from the individual’s reported non-trivial issues.<br>
            <sup>55</sup> This analysis draws on four key World Justice Project studies: <i class="inline">Global Insights on Access to Justice; Measuring the Justice Gap; Dissecting the Justice Gap in 104 Countries</i>; and <i class="inline">Disparities, Vulnerabilities, and Harnessing Data for People-Centered Justice</i>.
          </small>
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
