<section id="findingsSection6b" class="ExecutiveFindings_general">
  <div class="container pt-5">
    <div class="row justify-content-center">
      <div class="col-md-11 mt-2">
        <h6 class="font-medium text-[#575796]">
          Sample Size and Sociodemographic distribution
        </h6>
        <p>
          The General Population Poll in Italy represents a total achieved sample size of 3,844 people, distributed across the five NUTS-1 regions as follows: 770 interviews in the North-West region (ITC), 766 interviews in the North-East region (ITH), 766 interviews in the Centre region (ITI), 774 interviews in the Southern region (ITF), and 768 interviews in the Islands (ITG).
        </p>
        <p>
          In terms of sociodemographic information, the sample is distributed as follows:
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 text-gray-700">
          <li class="pl-0">
            <p>
              51.8% of respondents identified as female, 48.0% as male, and the remaining 0.2% identified as other.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li class="pl-0">
            <p>
              11.4% of respondents live in rural areas, while 88.6% live in urban areas.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li class="pl-0">
            <p>
              8.2% of respondents were between 18 and 24 years old, 12.6% were between 25 and 34, 15.1% were between 35 and 44, 19.3% were between 45 and 54, 17.2% were between 55 and 64, and 27.6% were over 65 years old.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          In addition to the achieved sample, 1,145 respondents were excluded from the initial pool because they either did not complete the questionnaire or failed to meet the quality control standards established by the WJP to ensure data reliability.
        </p>
        <h6 class="font-medium text-[#575796]">
          Data Validation
        </h6>
        <p>
          While there are inherent limitations in directly comparing Legal Needs Surveys (LNS) with other sources, such triangulation provides a more comprehensive perspective on how self-reported experiences align with the actual functioning of justice systems. The World Justice Project compared the general population poll against a range of external, third-party quantitative and qualitative sources. This triangulation strategy provided an extra layer of verification, highlighting potential inconsistencies while also contextualizing findings. By integrating multiple sources of evidence, WJP enhanced the robustness of the analysis and reduced the risk of systematic bias in the final results.
        </p>
        <h6 class="font-medium text-[#575796]">
          WJP Global Legal Needs Survey
        </h6>
        <p>
          The survey is designed to capture people’s experiences with justice problems and their attempts to resolve them. The survey begins by presenting respondents with a comprehensive list of nearly 40 situations that could be classified as justice problems. Respondents were asked whether they had encountered any of these issues in the two years preceding the survey. For each reported problem, they were also asked to rate its seriousness on a scale from 0 (least serious) to 10 (most serious).
        </p>
        <p>
          Respondents who reported to have experienced at least one justice problem are routed into the rest of the survey. To avoid overburdening respondents while maintaining analytical focus, the survey randomly selected one problem to serve as the basis for follow-up questions. However, this selection prioritized issues rated as non-trivial (a self-reported score of 4 or above on a scale of 0 to 10), ensuring that the analysis concentrated on problems that had a tangible impact on people’s lives. If all the problems that respondents reported to have experienced in the past two years are trivial, the survey randomly selects an issue from the whole list of reported problems. It is important to note that the indicators presented in this report are focused only on non-trivial issues.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
